Xenophanes of Colophon c. 570 – 475 BCE
Region / Tradition: Ionia / Magna Graecia (Greek)
School / Movement: Eleatic Pre-Socratic (Precursor)

Core Domains
Metaphysics: Pantheism/Monotheism (The One God).

Epistemology: Fallibilism; The distinction between belief (dokos) and certain truth.

Religion: Critique of anthropomorphism; Naturalism.

Science: Geology and Paleontology (study of fossils).

Central Questions
What problem(s) were they trying to solve: The immorality and absurdity of the Homeric gods (Zeus, Hera, etc.) who acted like flawed humans.

What tension or paradox defines their work: The tension between the human drive to know the divine and the inherent limitations of human perspective.

What question do they inherit: The Milesian search for a single Arche, but applied to the nature of God rather than just matter.

What question do they bequeath: "If we can't know the truth for certain, can we still get closer to it through inquiry?"

Key Ideas
Concept 1: Critique of Anthropomorphism: He famously noted that if horses or lions could draw, they would make their gods look like horses or lions.

Concept 2: The One God: A non-human, immobile, and eternal deity that "sways all things by the thought of his mind."

Concept 3: Fallibilism: The idea that "certain truth" is impossible for humans; we only have "opinions" that resemble the truth.

Concept 4: Fossil Evidence: He was the first to use fossils (shells found in mountains) to prove that the earth’s surface had changed over time and was once covered by sea.

Method / Style
Skeptical Rationalism and Social Critique.
Xenophanes used satirical poetry and logical reductio ad absurdum to dismantle traditional myths. He defined truth as something objective that exists, even if human "belief" can never fully grasp it.

Influences
The Milesians: Borrowed their naturalistic approach to explain weather (Iris/Rainbow as a cloud, not a goddess).

Homer and Hesiod: He acted as a "counter-influence," reacting strongly against their portrayal of the gods.

Impact
Immediate reception: Seen as a wandering poet-philosopher who challenged the very foundations of Greek religion.

Long-term influence: Directly inspired Parmenides and the Eleatic School; founded the tradition of Western Skepticism.

Modern relevance: A pioneer of the "Sociology of Religion" and the scientific method of using physical evidence (fossils) to reconstruct history.

Critiques
Famous objections: Aristotle later called him "somewhat naive" for not clearly defining whether his "One God" was material or immaterial.

Internal contradictions: He claimed no one can know the truth, yet he seemed very certain about the nature of his "One God."

Archetypal Summary
Xenophanes as the iconoclast who broke the mirrors of the gods to see the universe as it really is.

